data.label:
Lucita Azaro

"Now. Have you played 'Facts or Fiction' before?"

Elena Werner

"I still find this childish. In my day, if people wanted to get drunk, they got drunk."

Player_Romus

"My grandmother never would have tried to embezzle from the treasury."

Player_Romus_Italic

I picked up my glass and took a healthy sip. Lucita and Pabel did the same.

Elena Werner

"Ask me anything about Markian ducats and Rezenid medallions."

Player_Romus

"Ms. Werner, if you please."

Player_Romus

"Go ahead, Mr. Esquibel."

Player_Romus

"I'll give it a go myself, if you don't mind."

Narrator

My councilors looked at each other with no small amount of excitement.

Narrator

I felt tired, but not drunk. I racked my brain for ideas.

Player_Romus

"I have a bullet wound on the back of my leg in the exact shape of the Pales Administrative District."

Player_Romus

"I was unfaithful to my wife."

Player_Romus

"Back when I was the Party Prince, I got so intoxicated that I mistook a priceless Markian vase for a urinal."

Player_Romus

"My great-grandfather King Xavi II never actually had a mustache. I drew one on his royal portrait a long time ago."

Player_Romus

"If I weren't king, I think I'd like to be a farmer."

Player_Romus

"I can belch the Rizian national anthem."

Narrator

The others exchanged troubled looks. Laurento cautiously spoke up.

Player_Romus

"Growing up in Palas Toras, I once mistook a priceless Markian vase for a urinal."

Player_Romus

"Princess Lena was my first kiss."

Player_Romus

"Sometimes I worry I'm *too* benevolent."

Lucita Azaro

"As you wish, Your Majesty."

Narrator

Lucita gave me a sly smile.

Laurento Esquibel

"When I'm in a diplomatic meeting that I know is trivial, I draw caricatures instead of taking notes."

Pabel Adria

"His Majesty once had me weed a patch of stinging nettles for his amusement. Little did he know I rather enjoyed the sensation."

Player_Romus

"You're not really doodling during meetings, are you?"

Pabel Adria

"My father once made me weed a patch of stinging nettles as punishment for shirking off on duty. Little did he know I rather enjoyed the sensation."

Lucita Azaro

"Well done, Ms. Werner. Who's next?"

Player_Romus

"You're a lover, not a fighter. You wouldn't have instigated a duel."

Elena Werner

"I've head the duel story a hundred times, Laurento. You didn't challenge the mayor of Sallabes. It was the Earl of Jales."

Player_Romus

"What was the duel about?"

Player_Romus

"This means you've been treating serious diplomatic matters with frivolity, Mr. Esquibel."

Laurento Esquibel

"Unimportant ones only, Your Majesty. I assure you I take my position very seriously."

Player_Romus

"I don't mind as long as the job gets done."

Narrator

Lucita drained her glass as Elena, Pabel and I watched.

Narrator

Lucita drained her glass. Elena watched with a triumphant smirk.

Narrator

Laurento gave a sigh of relief. Lucita tapped the side of her glass for attention.

Player_Romus

"I would know if Pabel had written poetry."

Narrator

Pabel smiled grimly.

Pabel Adria

"Actually, the poetry part is true."

Narrator

My butler seemed reluctant to speak. He gave a graceful nod.

Pabel Adria

"I once overheard a Rumburgian royal valet make a demeaning comment about Queen Mother Estela during a diplomatic visit. I persuaded our chef to put an excessive amount of pepper in his food at the staff dinner."

Narrator

Pabel shifted in his seat.

Player_Romus

"You played a dangerous game with Rumburg. What if he'd found out and told Beatrice?"

Player_Romus

"How brutal of your father."

Pabel Adria

"He was worried I was distracting you from your princely duties."

Laurento Esquibel

"Wait, let me guess..."

Laurento Esquibel

"I was the shadow to your light

A silent witness to the burden you bore.

A chasm yawns between us now,

Eager to be filled with talk, with touch."

Lucita Azaro

"Well. Whichever palace maid he wrote that for is one lucky girl."

Narrator

Laurento raised an eyebrow.

Player_Romus

"Sometimes I wish the '26 uprising had succeeded."

Laurento Esquibel

"Intriguing, dear Duchess. But false. Azaros don't fall prey to superstition."

Narrator

Elena took a prim sip of her wine. Lucita continued with a mischievous smile on her face.

Player_Romus_Italic

Elena and I drank. Lucita continued with a mischievous smile on her face.

Lucita Azaro

"I find it invigorating to wear nothing at all beneath my uniform."

Narrator

She looked down in embarrassment.

Lucita Azaro

"If you'd like to be helpful, you can fetch us a new bottle. This one's almost empty."

Player_Romus

"I don't actually like wine."

Pabel Adria

"It isn't important."

Player_Romus

"I feel so goddamn lonely all the time."

Laurento Esquibel

"Of course you were faithful to Princess Lena, Your Majesty. That was the lie."

Laurento Esquibel

"Of course you weren't glad when King Valero died, Your Majesty. That was the lie."

Player_Romus

"No, that was the truth."

Narrator

The others quickly nodded their assent. I could see Lucita scrutinizing me closely.

Lucita Azaro

"So..."

Lucita Azaro

"You must like wine, Your Majesty. You've been drinking enough of it tonight."

Laurento Esquibel

"The vase story must be a lie. It's too embarrassing."

Laurento Esquibel

"The mustache story must be a lie."

Laurento Esquibel

"You can't really belch the Rizian national anthem."

Player_Romus

"Actually, that one was true."

Elena Werner

"Don't you remember, Laurento? His Majesty used to be quite the hell-raiser."

Elena Werner

"It's not a complete impossibility."

Narrator

The others nodded their assent.

Lucita Azaro

"The Pales Administrative District? May we see it, Your Majesty?"

Player_Romus

"No, you may not."

Narrator

I pulled my collar aside and showed her the scar.

Narrator

Lucita sat back in her chair, disappointed.

Lucita Azaro

"The Porte Drazon Derby? That must have been a rush."

Player_Romus

"Sure."

Player_Romus

"Yes, that sounds like a wise idea."

Player_Romus

"But we were just getting to the good stuff."

Narrator

I suddenly became acutely aware of how much wine I'd had to drink. Pabel helped keep me steady as we made our way upstairs to my suite.

Player_Romus

"Well guessed."

Player_Romus

"Yes, I kissed women. Lots and lots of women. They had breasts and everything."

Narrator

He swiftly ushered me inside and took off my coat.

Pabel Adria

"So... that poem... those feelings..."

Player_Romus

"Wait. Don't go."

Player_Romus

"It's fine, Pabel. I won't tell a soul."

Player_Romus

"Please exercise more discretion going forward. I can't have word get out that my butler is a pervert."

Narrator

Pabel hurriedly backed away from me.

Narrator

He rushed out, closing the door behind him.

Narrator

Relief blossomed across Pabel's face. He bowed.

Pabel Adria

"I hope you enjoyed your evening, Your Majesty."

Player_Romus

"Be honest. Do you still feel that way about me now?"

Player_Romus

"I still remember my first kiss."

Player_Romus_Italic

I leaned forward and kissed him.

Player_Romus

"We can't. You're my subordinate."

Player_Romus

"This isn't right. You've had more to drink than I have."

Narrator

Pabel didn't turn around.

Pabel Adria

"You should get some sleep, Your Majesty. It's late."

Player_Romus

"It was a beautiful poem."

Player_Romus

"Yes. Pabel, remind me to call important meetings more often."

Post-Game Bedtime Fallout -- Pabel

Post-Game Bedtime Fallout -- Pabel

Narrator

My butler guided me up stairways and through corridors to my suite on the top floor.

Pabel Adria

"Thank you."

Player_Romus

"I don't share your feelings. But you're still my friend."

Pabel Adria

"Good night."

Pabel Adria

"I was reckless to submit it for publication. I... I must have missed you that much."

Player_Romus

"Nothing can happen between us. It's too dangerous."

Pabel Adria

"I know."

Narrator

It was some time before we broke apart. Pabel stared into my eyes, his breath ragged.

Narrator

He left the room and gently closed the door behind him.

Player_Romus

"God. I never felt that with Lena."

Pabel Adria

"Good night, Your Majesty."

Player_Romus

"Needless to say, I hope this means my secrets are also safe with you."

Player_Romus

"Nobody can ever know about this. Nobody."

Pabel Adria

"Bi mare volu..."

Pabel Adria

"As my king commands."

Narrator

With some difficulty, I undressed and crawled into bed.

Player_Romus

"I'll help find you a lover more suited to a man of your station."

Pabel Adria

"Please, Your Majesty. I think you have the wrong idea."

Narrator

With some difficulty, I undressed and crawled into bed.

Narrator

He looked me in the eye and nodded.

Narrator

He smiled politely.

Narrator

I was just starting to drift off to sleep when a soft knock came at the door.

Narrator

Lucita was standing there, still dressed in the beaded gown she'd worn earlier.

Narrator

She gave me a scornful look.

Player_Romus

"Of course, Duchess Azaro."

Player_Romus

"A message? What is it?"

Player_Romus

"No, it can wait until tomorrow."

Lucita Azaro

"Are you sure? It's extremely sensitive."

Player_Romus

"All right. Please enter."

Lucita Azaro

"But the zipper starts right here."

Player_Romus_Italic

I took her hands and pulled her closer. We stood still for a moment, regarding each other.

Player_Romus

"What was the message from Wehlen?"

Lucita Azaro

"If anything, I'm taking advantage of you."

Player_Romus

"So... does this count as an important meeting?"

Lucita Azaro

"Let them."

Lucita Azaro

"We're alone. Everyone else has passed out. Who's going to say anything?"

Player_Romus

"I respect you as a councilor, Duchess Azaro. That's all."

Lucita Azaro

"Why don't you find out for yourself, Your Majesty?"

Narrator

I undressed and got into bed.

Player_Romus

"Truth, lies, what does it matter? Everyone's just going to believe what they want to anyway."

Player_Romus

"You all guessed wrong! Why aren't you drinking?"

Player_Romus

"Life, Duchess Azaro. Life is a lie."

Laurento Esquibel

"Goodnight, Your Majesty. Thank you for an enlightening time."

Narrator

Lucita and the others quickly drained their glasses.

Player_Romus

"I'm your king. That's all you need to know about me."

Player_Romus

"That was a lie too. The King's allowed to lie more than once."

Narrator

Laurento uneasily pushed back his chair.

Narrator

Laurento's mouth hung open.

Narrator

Lucita raised her glass and drank a sip anyway.

Laurento Esquibel

"Forgive me, but this elder statesman is going to call it an evening. Thank you for an enlightening time."

Elena Werner

"Yes, we've all learned enough about each other already. Possibly too much."

Player_Romus

"The more intimately we know each other, the better we can defend each other."

Narrator

She smiled guiltily.

Player_Romus

"Your behavior towards me is completely inappropriate. You should be ashamed of yourself."

Narrator

She lowered her eyes.

Player_Romus

"I didn't make a complete ass of myself, did I?"

Narrator

Laurento pushed back his chair.

Narrator

Out of the corner of my eye, I saw Pabel give me an uneasy look. Lucita didn't appear to notice.

Player_Romus

"I did. But none of them compared."

Narrator

There was an awkward silence for a moment.

Pabel Adria

"Even if you did, I doubt anyone will remember what was said."

Player_Romus

"Thank you, Pabel. Good night."

Player_Romus

"I did before you ruined it."

Player_Romus_Italic

I leaned down and kissed her. She grabbed me by the suit lapels and returned the kiss with ferocity.

Narrator

She guided my hand to the small of her back.

Narrator

She looked me square in the eye.

Lucita Azaro

"And as your war councilor, I need to be able to defend you very, very well."

Lucita Azaro

"I-- I'm sorry. I misunderstood."

Lucita Azaro

"This never happened."

Lucita Azaro

"I'm right here. Isn't this more efficient?"

Narrator

She practically ran out of the room.

Narrator

She gave a flustered bow and left the room.

Narrator

I shut the door and got back into bed. I slept more soundly than I had in months.

Lucita Azaro

"I will, Your Majesty. Sleep well."

Pabel Adria

"I have my doubts about that one as well."

Elena Werner

"But wanting to be a farmer? That's not His Majesty's style."

Narrator

Everyone looked at me.

Pabel Adria

"Shall I escort you to your quarters, Your Majesty?"

Narrator

My councilors and I said our goodbyes. They dispersed to the rooms they were staying in.

Narrator

My councilors, Pabel and I said our goodnights. I headed to my suite on the top floor.

Player_Romus

"It doesn't matter. It's a silly game."

Player_Romus

"I only *wish* I could belch 'On Shores Of Gold'."

Player_Romus

"No, I never won the Derby."

Pabel Adria

"If I may be so bold, I've seen that for myself. I'll throw my lot in with Duchess Azaro."

Player_Romus

"I don't really want to be a farmer."

Player_Romus

"What can I say? I like knowing where my food comes from."

Player_Romus

"Everything was true! Now everybody has to drink."

Elena Werner

"That's what I said, Your Majesty."

Lucita Azaro

"Ah. A pity, Your Majesty."

Lucita Azaro

"But that's not how--

Lucita Azaro

"The vase story must be a lie. It's too embarrassing."

Laurento Esquibel

"Agreed."

Laurento Esquibel

"Agreed."

Lucita Azaro

"Agreed."

Lucita Azaro

"Agreed."

Lucita Azaro

"Agreed."

Narrator

Pabel cleared his throat.

Lucita Azaro

"I should have guessed that."

Lucita Azaro

"So..."

Narrator

She reached for her glass. It was empty.

Lucita Azaro

"Butler!"

Laurento Esquibel

"I envy the flowers, unabashed in their display.

They do not hide their nature, nor fear the light of day.

The fragrance of their open hearts fills the air with dreams,

A scent of possibilities, or so it truly seems."

Laurento Esquibel

"Yet here I stand, a silent ghost, amongst the floral cheer,\n\nA figure lost in what could be, held back by hidden fear."

Player_Romus

"That was beautiful. I had no idea."

Player_Romus

"That's not serious poetry. One might recite it at a ladies' tea."

Narrator

Silence descended around our table. Lucita spoke up brightly.

Pabel Adria

"I-- I think you have the wrong idea. Let's just both forget about all of this."

Player_Romus

"We both know that I don't. I've spent years atoning for the things we did as boys. You should consider the same."

Player_Romus

"I admit I have harbored similar feelings. But I have never once acted on them, because I'm a God-fearing man."

Pabel Adria

"I-- I will."

Pabel Adria

"I'm truly sorry, Your Majesty. I should never have brought it up."

Pabel Adria

"Thank you. I won't mention a word of this going forward."

Player_Romus

"I care about you as a friend. But I don't share your proclivities."

Narrator

A powerful sensation washed over me, like that of finally arriving home after a long, exhausting journey. I took a step back.

Pabel Adria

"The butler's quarters here are connected by an adjoining door. Just knock if you need me."

Player_Romus

"I'll never forget what we had back then. But it's over."

Player_Romus

"Before *and* after, I might add."

Narrator

Pabel took a deep breath. He smoothed his hair back.

Pabel Adria

"Forgive me, I dropped my wine glass. I'll have it cleared up at once."

Narrator

I lurched unsteadily to my feet. Pabel rushed to my side and took my arm.

Player_Romus

"Fear of what, Pabel?"

Player_Romus

"Wait. Your poem. I think I know what it was about."

Narrator

He froze.

Player_Romus

"Whatever secret you may be harboring, it's safe with me."

Narrator

Relief blossomed across his face.

Pabel Adria

"Thank you, Your Majesty."

Pabel Adria

"You are the king, Your Majesty. You need not fear the sun."

Narrator

Lucita picked up her glass and took a healthy sip.
